title: For Sale:  Bavarian M1842 Rifled Musket
postcontent: Up for sale is a solid example of the Bavarian M1842 Rifled-musket, one of the most rarely encountered arms of the Civil War. With the exception of the ramrod this example is complete and fully functioning, including its signature long rand leaf sight. This example has a chunk of wood missing behind the front band, but is otherwise intact. The right side of the butt stock has a set of initals, L.P, carved into it. The metal has an attractive chocolate color over most parts. There has been some cleaning done in an apparent attempt to reveal markings around the breech. The gun is bare of markings, save for an allignment mark at the rear of the breech and tang. The bolster and lock show some old pitting from field usage. The bore still shows good rifling, although it is dark. The stock is in good condition apart from the noted defects. It has typical usage wear and bruising, but no real cracks or splits. This is a great example of one of the rarer imported arms of the Civil War, with an estimated 3,000 being imported by Federal agents and arms speculators. Shipping is not included in the price, but I figure it will run around $40 with insrance. If you would like additional pictures I will be happy to send them.I posted this listing earlier in the day and it way flagged as a scam. title: For Sale:  Confederate Altered M1816 Musket
postcontent: Up for sale is a nice example of a genuine Confederate altered Model 1816 flintlock musket. This musket started life as a M1822 (M1816 type 2) produced by Marine T. Wickham of Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. It may have been one of the 160 brown finished Wickham muskets delivered to the Commonwealth of Virginia under the Militia Act of 1808. In any event this musket was percussion altered via the brazed bolster method by the Union Manufacturing Company of Richmond in 1861 or 1862. This firm was the second most prolific alterer of flintlock musket for the State of Virginia, having converted between 10,060 and 11,315 muskets for the state. The firm also sold component parts to the Confederate Government as well. This example has the typical round bottomed bolster of a Union Manufacturing alteration, although it lacks the "U" stamping on the barrel, lock, or hammer that "Confederate Rifles and Muskets" correlates to the muskets. However, the book also makes note that not all examples bare the "U" stamping. I have two additional examples in my collection that lack the "U" markings as well. Unfortunately this musket was cleaned at some point. The metal is turning back to a pewter to gunmetal fininsh and has no active rust. The lock is functional, although the cone is missing. There is some scattered light pitting over the gun, which is much more noticeable around the bolster and lock. The tang was broken at one point and has been repaired via brazing, which may date to the percussion alteration. The ramrod is included, although it is about 1/2 inch short, having no implement threads. The front sling swivel is broken. The stock was also sanded, but is in remarkably good shape, and still has nice definition to the lock pannels, etc. The stock flat is devoid of any cartouches, and may have not had any to begin with. The biggest drawback to this gun is that hammer, which is not a Confederate hammer, but more likely a replacement from a Henry Leman alteration. It fits the gun well, and is a somewhat close representation of what the proper Union Manufacturing hammer should look like. All in all, this is a solid Confederate musket at a price that I doubt you will see one at any time soon. My first listing was flagged by someone who neglected to even give me the benefit of the doubt and message me concerning the validity of the post. I request that if you feel this post is spam or a scam you contact me so I can prove otherwise. Shipping is not inclued in the price, but I expect it to run about $50 with insurance. Pick-up and inspections are also welcome.Thanks for looking.
